  The Roadmap — In Priority Order

  Phase 1 — Close the Claude Code gap (highest leverage)

  1. Pre-generation context expansion loop: Before calling J-Prime, send a "planning prompt": "Here is the task and the primary file. What other files do you need to see to generate a correct patch?" J-Prime returns a list. JARVIS reads them. Then calls J-Prime again with full context. This is the single change that most closes the Claude Code gap.

  2. Tool-use interface for J-Prime: Give J-Prime callable tools it can invoke mid-generation: search_code(pattern), read_file(path), list_files(glob), run_tests(paths). J-Prime decides what to look at. JARVIS executes and returns results. This is how Claude Code actually works internally.

  3. Semantic opportunity detectors (beyond cyclomatic complexity)
  - Security scanner: hardcoded secrets, SQL injection patterns, unsafe deserialization
  - Dead code detector: functions defined but never called
  - Test coverage gap detector: files with no corresponding test
  - Deprecated API usage: asyncio.coroutine, imp, optparse, etc.
  - Regression detector: files that have been patched multiple times and keep failing

  Phase 2 — Close the Reactor feedback loop

  4. Post-patch benchmarking: After every applied patch: run the test suite, record pass rate, latency, and code quality score. Write this back to PerformanceRecordPersistence with the op_id and the patch hash. Now JARVIS knows "this patch made tests go from 87% → 94%."

  5. Model quality attribution: After Reactor delivers a new model: run a benchmark on the last 20 task types that were in the training batch. Record delta. Write: "Model v3.2 (trained on 47 ouroboros experiences) improved auth-task success rate by 23%." Now the loop has a measurement at the end.

  6. Curriculum signal back to Reactor: Based on where JARVIS is still failing, tell Reactor what to train on next. Instead of "here are experiences, do something with them" — "here are experiences, weighted by how much JARVIS still struggles with these patterns."

  Phase 3 — Build the self-model

  7. Unified self-representation document: A persistent JSON/markdown file JARVIS maintains: what it's worked on, what approaches succeeded, what failed, what the current architecture looks like from its perspective. Injected into every J-Prime prompt header. J-Prime generates with awareness of what JARVIS is.

  8. Cross-session pattern recognition: A background process that reads the ledger weekly and writes: "Files modified more than 3 times: backend/auth/middleware.py (5×), backend/api/handler.py (4×). Recurring failure pattern: async timeout in middleware." This feeds into which files get priority next cycle.

  9. Failure archaeology: When an improvement attempt fails, write a structured postmortem to the self-model: what was tried, what the error was, what the hypothesis was. Next time JARVIS touches the same file, J-Prime gets that history in the prompt.

  Phase 4 — Communication and autonomy quality

  10. Structured diff explanation: Instead of "change applied to prime," show the user: which functions changed, what the before/after logic difference is, what tests were added, what the risk is. Narrated via voice + displayed in TUI with expandable sections.

  11. Proactive risk communication before applying: Before writing any file: "This patch touches backend/auth/middleware.py which is imported by 14 other files. Three tests currently cover it. Applying in 30 seconds unless you say stop." Human stays in the loop without having to watch constantly.

  ---
  The most impactful single change is Phase 1, item 1 — the pre-generation context expansion loop. Everything else compounds on top of that. Without it, JARVIS is fundamentally a "repair the file you point at" system. With it, JARVIS can understand a problem before solving it — which is the actual core of what Claude Code does.


